| RAM      | **16 GB**                            | Good for higher thread counts and larger JVM heap       |
| Disk     | NVMe 218 GB                          | Fast and large enough                                   |
| Network  | Standard 1 GbE                       | Suitable for distributed testing                        |
| OS       | Ubuntu 24.04 LTS                     | Fully compatible                                        |


New “Super Machine” Slave

| Resource | New “Super Machine” Slave   | General JMeter Recommendation                          |
| -------- | --------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------ |
| CPU      | 12 cores / 24 threads       | Ideal for high-scale tests and complex scripts      |
| RAM      | **32 GB**                   | Great for large heap sizes and thousands of threads |
| Disk     | NVMe 500 GB                 | Excellent speed and capacity                        |
| Network  | 1–10 GbE (10 GbE preferred) | Optimal for high-volume distributed testing         |
| OS       | Ubuntu 24.04 LTS            | Fully compatible                                    |


Implement performance configuration optimizations on the JMeter master and slave nodes.
Run the Azure pipeline directly from the JMeter master server .31 to minimize additional network traffic between the performance test and pipeline execution.



| Configuration                         | Advantages                                  | Disadvantages                                |
| ------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| Master + Slave with increased RAM     | Leverages existing hardware, lower cost     | Still a small distributed environment        |
| Master + Super Slave                  | Excellent load capacity, future scalability | Higher cost                                  |
| Single Super Machine (no distributed) | Simplicity, zero Master–Slave latency       | Single point of failure; limited to one host |


